general? This book offers a provocative examination of globalization, examining the lives of the women at the center of these new global dynamics. Arguing that society is facing multiple crises of care, the authors develop a new framework for understanding the interplay of globalization, gender, and carework. In four original essays, they examine gender, race, and class inequality; migration, citizenship, and the politics of social control; the evolving meanings of motherhood; and new social definitions of carework and the personal transformation of careworkers. Excerpts from the classic works in the field as well as recent cutting-edge research studies support the examination of each of these growing global crises.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Bridget, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnwary, Afroza, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAvila, Ernestine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlair-Loy, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBose, Christine E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aChang, Grace, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCheng, Shu-Ju Ada, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristopherson, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEnloe, Cynthia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFolbre, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFraser, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlenn, Evelyn Nakano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, Mar